<font color="#FF0000">SEATO AND CIVIL WAR</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jan  4  9:09:42 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
The SEATO treaty comes into effect if one is able to deny that the war in Vietnam was a *civil war*. The treaty was set up as a means of protecting countries in SE Asia from *external* forces. <br><br>
I recently read, and would be interested in hearing more about, how the Soviets approached the US in the late 1950's with a plan to permanently partition North and South Vietnam - thus making them de facto states with their own sovereignty. NEITHER North or South wanted any part of this arrangement. They both considered VN as one.<br><br>
Our main concern was containing communism, of course. But, during WWII we allied ourselves with Ho Chi Minh and his communist forces against the Japanese. While we can excuse this arrangement as being expedient, Ho looked upon it as the next logical step towards independence from French colonialism.<br><br>
As far as us having a &quot;right&quot; to fight in Vietnam because we were invited, it is first necessary to deny that the war was a civil one. It has to be proven that an &quot;invasion&quot; took place, and that there was a limited South Vietnamese communist (VC) presence in South Vietnam. <br><br>
There were large numbers of VC as far south as the Delta where much of the fighting took place during the early 1960's. In northern I Corps many communist units were NVA. It wasn't until after Tet of 1968 that they infiltrated the rest of the south in large numbers.<br><br>
The major blunder of the South Vietnamese government was their alienation of the Buddhist population which comprised 85% of the south AND their failure to address a land reform issue. The VC exploited land reform to their advantage.<br><br>
Getting back to whether or not Vietnam was two countries: Both North and South Vietnam state in their constitutions that there is only 1 Vietnam. <br><br>
The country was partitioned as part of the Geneva Treaty in 1954. Shortly after, the CIA and Edward Lansdale arranged for &quot;stay behinds&quot; in the north to sabotage the rebuilding of North Vietnam. The CIA also maneuvered Vietnamese emperor Bao Dai into abdicating and transferring his power to Ngo Dinh Diem - an avowed anti-communist Catholic. The Eisenhower administration needed someone with whom they could work in establishing American power in the absence of the defeated French. An &quot;invitation&quot; was a mere formality.<br><br>
The real trick in beginning to understand is to look at the early years, after the defeat of the French through the eyes of the Vietnamese, who were less interested in an overall world view (like the US) than they were in achieving independence from foreign dominance.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


